                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Riart wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Well, anything regarding iptables on your localhost won't do anything for you if the campus network is blocking ports and IP's.
<br />

<br />
So, to your question if I can get this right.  Your living on campus, they provide a residential network and they use a *nix firewall?  All ports are blocked?  They also are blocking SOE's IP's?
<br />

<br />
What issues are you having when you try to use the campus' network with EQ?
<br />

<br />
BTW, if they use iptables, all they need is to allow incoming connections that are  related and established (which they already should) and all loopback networks full access (depending on the firewall)
<br />

<br />
I don't know about your network admin, but I seriously question the competence of the administrators for the campus I live on.  They show the intelligence of someone who hasn't even read a manual.
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Yes, I moved into college accomodation (ie onto campus) for the final part of my degree, after having lived "out" for the whole time previously.
<br />

<br />
The buildings I'm in are connected to the New College network, which is connected to JANet (Joint Academic Network, that all universities in the UK connect to).
<br />

<br />
There is an Ethernet socket in my room.  When I first tried connecting to the network through it, I had to register.  Since then, I can access web pages.
<br />

<br />
When I attempt to run the EQ patcher, I get
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Could not establish a connection.  Please check your network connection or contact <a href="mailto:eqtech@soe.sony.com">eqtech@soe.sony.com</a></td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
When I attempt to run EQ bypassing the patcher, I get
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">A connection to the server could not be reached.  Please check your connection to make sure you are online.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
If I try to run Magelo update program, I get
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">A connection attempt failed because the connected party did not properly respond after a period of time, or established connection failed because connected host has failed to respond.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Both EQ and Magelo worked just fine while I was on ADSL, and on dialup, and still work on dialup.
<br />

<br />
This leads me to believe that ITOfficer configured the firewall to block everything, then allow certain ports etc, to enable eg web browsing.
<br />

<br />
I sent him a polite email with a list of IPs and ports that EQ uses (and the link to the <a href="http://eqlive.station.sony.com/support/tech_support/ts_network_support_firewall_proxy_info.jsp" target="_blank" class="postlink">Firewall/Proxy info</a>).  I did copy the information to the email so he didn't actually  need to click the link if he didn't want to.
<br />

<br />
Originally when I asked him, he said that it shouldn't be a problem to allow them.  Then he saw the list and said that he'd have to ask the guy that wrote the firewall software about it ("because it was blowing a huge hole in the firewall").  Then he said that he'd get round to it, but it wasn't a high priority because it was "just a game".
<br />

<br />
I could understand the final part as the beginning of the new academic year is bound to be busy (and I work part time at the University Computer Services Helpdesk, and I could see how many extra ppl came in with problems).  It's now third week, and over three weeks since I first asked him, and I know that things have slowed down (certainly the last two weeks have been much quieter at helpdesk).
<br />

<br />
I sent him an email last week saying I appreciated that he was busy due to the beginning of term, and was there anything I could do to help that would cut down on his workload and allow my connections faster.  I didn't get any reply to that, so I went round there this morning.  He just said he knew what I was going to ask and he hadn't got round to it yet coz he was "busy".  When I asked him if he'd received my email he just slung out "do you know IPtable commands?".  He didn't even acknowledge receiving the email, but did reinforce that "you have to write a new rule for each IP address" <img src="images/smiles/eusa_eh.gif" alt="eusa_eh.gif" border="0" /> Even I know that once you've written one, you can cut/paste for the others! <img src="images/smiles/eusa_doh.gif" alt="eusa_doh.gif" border="0" /> 
<br />

<br />
From what I've heard (friend of mine on the ITSS discussion list that I only recently joined), he has a reputation of being paranoid when it comes to allowing stuff <img src="images/smiles/icon_sad.gif" alt="icon_sad.gif" border="0" />  Another person (my neighbour) said he's "lazy".
<br />

<br />
The University IT policy says that "reasonable social and recreational purposes" of the connection are allowed, unless on the list of things that aren't allowed (pr0n, etc).  I pretty much only play EQ with my bf (LDR) and friends of mine from Denmark that I only get to see about once a year (ie: for social and recreational purposes)
<br />

<br />
Basically he's dragging his feet.  I'd hoped that I might be able to prompt him into action if I laid a suggestion in front of him, but unfortunately my coder friend wasn't on MSN today so I couldn't get any suggestions there <img src="images/smiles/icon_sad.gif" alt="icon_sad.gif" border="0" /></span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
