                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Heh,
<br />

<br />
  That's just silly, I mean I can understand reigning in filesharing programs and the like and rate-limiting their usage at the very least.    But EQ?   EQ is firewall-friendly, so they must only allow very specific applications ( such as web traffic and maybe even redirecting you to transparent proxy servers ( which would block porn, etc if they wanted ) to traverse their Internet connection(s).
<br />

<br />
  Nothing has to be done at the firewall end from the viewpoint of a sane policy standpoint.  Any stateful firewall can provide safe state even using Port  Address Translation for EQ traffic, as it does not rely on traffic to be initiated by the EQ servers.
<br />

<br />
  So obviously, they have a very restrictive policy.  If you can't get them to change it you can bypass their efforts fairly easily ( most firewalls don't have the necessary heuristics to stop piercing/tunneling ) by piercing the firewall so-to-speak.    Essentially, you can setup a tunnel utilizing ports that are allowed by their firewall ( i.e. SSH tunnels, HTTP tunnels, etc ) and  basically proxy your connection to EQ that way.    You'll need a non-restricted outside host to accomplish this however.
<br />

<br />
   There are several approaches and several different pieces of software that you can glue together to get the job done.   I suggest doing some research.
<br />

<br />

<br />
Good luck in your subversion efforts!</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
