                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">As a few others have eluded, your PC is the one making and breaking the connections not EQ's. My guess is the person doing the firewalls (Iptables), just decided to nuke all outgoing traffic on ports in the EQ range(Most default firewall configs do this).  Any MIS with even a hint of knowledge should have no problem adding one line to give your IP address(group) unlimited outside access. 
<br />

<br />

<br />
  Think its more a trust thing then anything else.. 
<br />
 
<br />
Example of command to add service for one IP. 
<br />
 
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold"> iptables -A INPUT -i inside ip address  -d 0/0 -j ACCEPT</span> 
<br />
Replace inside ip address with your computers ip address.  They may want to change the 0/0 after the -d, to the ipaddress/mask for the card/device that connects to the internet if they do not want you to have access to other connected networks on campus.
<br />
 
<br />
 This is the breakdown of the above command.
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">iptables (firewall program)
<br />
-A (append to current settings)
<br />
INPUT (examine traffic coming to the  firewall)
<br />
-i ipaddress (ip address of your computer)
<br />
-d 0/0 (destination ip address and mask, 0/0 mean all ip addresses)
<br />
 -j ACCEPT (go to/ jump when anything matches the above values, to ACCEPT)
<br />
</span>
<br />

<br />
 For 2.4 kernels and above, "service iptables save" will save the configuration. "service iptables restart" will reset the iptables to original settings (before you entered your command, as long as you have not typed "service iptables save") 
<br />
 
<br />
 Hope this helps..</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
