<br />
Thanks again!</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
edit: Maybe I should explain a little bit.  (Technical explanation if you care, otherwise skip to the next paragraph)  These xx.xx.xx.xx/xx specify IP address ranges with a network address and subnet mask.  Using decimal numbers as a clarifying example, if I want to specify a range of numbers from say 30-39, I can say I have a base number 30 and a mask of 10.  The 1 in the mask means the digit in the tens place of the base number (3) is a constant and the 0 means the digit in the ones place can be anything.  The address mask pairs use the same concept except with 32-bit binary numbers instead of 2 digit decimal numbers.  If I want to specify the range 128.128.128.0 through 128.128.128.255 (or 128.128.128.*), I can say I have a network address 128.128.128.0 and a subnet mask 255.255.255.0:
<br />
10000000.10000000.10000000.00000000 is the network address
<br />
11111111.11111111.11111111.00000000 is the mask.
<br />
So anywhere we have a zero in the mask, the corresponding digit in the address can be 0 or 1.  So where does the /24 come from?  Basically if the mask is just a bunch of leading ones followed by zeros, for simplicity you can just write how many ones there are in the mask.  You could alternatively give iptables the full mask, like 128.128.128.0/255.255.255.0.  I'm not sure if this made much sense but perhaps it helped.  Now back to your regularly scheduled post.
<br />

<br />
It depends, for example 64.37.148.* is equivalent to 64.37.148.0/24.  When you get into these 199.108.4* there is no single exact address netmask pair because the addresses are based on their decimal equivalents when they're in binary, so you can either just go ahead and do 199.108.0.0/16 by default and get the rest of them at the same time or you can figure out the equivalents (or THEY should since THEY'RE the network people and should know this):
<br />
199.108.40.0 is 199.108.00101000.00000000
<br />
199.108.49.255 is 199.108.00110001.11111111
<br />
so a closer answer is 199.108.32.0/19 and the exact answer is 199.108.40.0/21 AND 199.108.48.0/23.  Really I don't think it matters much if you cover some extra addresses (though they might have a different opinion); I'm surprised they have so restrictive of a firewall in the first place.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
